Here's the complete migration analysis and ASP.NET Core (.NET 8) replacement.

## Pattern Classification

| Usage | Pattern | Replacement |
|-------|---------|-------------|
| `Response.End()` | ASP.NET request termination | Return from action method |
| `Response.Redirect(url, true)` | ASP.NET request termination | Return `Redirect()` result |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | ThreadAbortException as control flow | Remove entirely |

## Migrated Code (ASP.NET Core / .NET 8)

```csharp
public class ReportController : Controller
{
    // Web Forms event handlers become MVC action methods returning IActionResult.
    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Export()
    {
        var data = GenerateReport();

        // Response.Clear / AddHeader / Write / End all collapse into a single
        // FileContentResult. The framework handles headers and flushing.
        return File(
            System.Text.Encoding.UTF8.GetBytes(data),
            "text/csv",
            "report.csv");
    }

    [HttpPost]
    public IActionResult Redirect()
    {
        if (!User.Identity?.IsAuthenticated ?? true)
        {
            // Response.Redirect(url, true) → return Redirect().
            // No Thread.Abort, no exception — just a 302 response.
            return Redirect("/login");
        }

        try
        {
            ProcessRequest();
            return Redirect("/success");
        }
        // ThreadAbortException catch block is removed entirely — it no longer
        // exists in .NET 8 and was only needed because Redirect(url, true)
        // called Thread.Abort internally.
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            LogError(ex);
            return Redirect("/error");
        }
    }
}
```

## Key Pitfalls

1. **`Response.End()` doesn't exist in ASP.NET Core.** Don't try to replicate it with `HttpResponse.CompleteAsync()` — just return an `IActionResult`. The framework flushes and closes the response.

2. **`Response.Redirect(url)` exists in Core but doesn't short-circuit.** Code after it *keeps running*. If you call it mid-method without returning, subsequent code will execute and may corrupt the response. Always pair with `return`.

3. **Removing the `ThreadAbortException` catch can unmask bugs.** The old catch block silently swallowed exceptions from `Response.Redirect`. If `ProcessRequest()` threw a different exception type that was accidentally caught by a broader clause, you'll now see it. Review your error handling.

4. **`User.Identity` can be `null` in Core.** Use null-conditional (`?.IsAuthenticated`) — the Framework version never returned null but Core can when no auth middleware is configured.

5. **Web Forms postback model is gone.** `btnExport_Click(object sender, EventArgs e)` becomes an `[HttpPost]` action. Wire your form to post to the action route, not to a server control event.

6. **File downloads: don't write to `Response.Body` manually.** Use `File()` helper — it sets `Content-Disposition`, `Content-Type`, and handles range requests/buffering correctly.

## What Was Removed and Why

| Removed | Reason |
|---------|--------|
| `Response.Clear()` | Core responses start empty; no buffered content to clear |
| `Response.AddHeader(...)` | Handled by `File()` result |
| `Response.Write(data)` | Handled by `File()` result |
| `Response.End()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 8 (`SYSLIB0006` lineage). Just return. |
| `Response.Redirect(url, true)` | The `true` (endResponse) overload doesn't exist in Core. Return `Redirect()` instead. |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `Thread.Abort` is never called — this exception can never be thrown in .NET 8 |
